         <abstract>
            <p>In the 1980s many conglomerates have begun a period of restructuring, with greater selectivity in acquisitions rather than the random diversification of the past. This study examines the financial performance of conglomerates in the 1980s over two stages of the business cycle, adjusting for empirical problems that may have biased previous studies. The evidence suggests that conglomerates in fewer industries perform better than more diversified firms, but the average performance of conglomerates is not significantly different from industry benchmarks.</p>
         </abstract>
